## Highlights

<ul> 
    <li> Catboost outperforms other models (including NN) with little preprocessing</li>
    <li> New model: RuleFit, discussed how it can be used as a model interpretability</li>
    <li> New resampling technique: SMOTENC, discussed how it helps improve the accuracy of the model</li>
    <li> New model interpretability: ALE plots, as an alternative to PDP plots</li>
    <li> open_count, subject length, country, and age as top predictor for predicting user opening an email</li>
</ul>

### Extract Dataset

The data was fetch from <a href="https://www.kaggle.com/c/open-shopee-code-league-marketing-analytics">kaggle</a> containing three csv files namely: <code>train.csv</code>, <code>test.csv</code>, and <code>users.csv</code>. train and test csv have similar features except that there is no <code>open_flag</code> for test.csv.

```python
df_train = pd.read_csv('train.csv')
df_test = pd.read_csv('test.csv')
df_users = pd.read_csv('users.csv')
```

<p style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;">
<b>Table 1. Data Description of train/test.csv.</b></p>

| Column |Description | 
| :---- |:----- |
|`country_code`| An integer code for the country where the user lives.                                            |
|`grass_date`| The date when the email was sent.                                                                  |
|`user_id`| the unique identifier of each user                                                                    |
|`subject_line_length`| the number of characters in the subject of the email                                      |
|`last_open_day`| How many days ago was the last time the user opened an email                                    |
|`last_login_day`| How many days ago the user last logged in its Shopee account                                   |
|`last_checkout_day`| How many days ago the user last purchased on Shopee                                         |
|`open_count_last_[10/30/60]_days`| the total number of email opens in the last N days.                           |
|`login_count_last_[10/30/60]_days`| the total number of user logins in the last N days.                          |
|`checkout_count_last_[10/30/60]_days`| the total number of checkouts (=purchases) by the user in the last N days.|
|`open_flag`| the target variable. Whether or not the email was opened.                                           |

<b>Table 3. Data Description of users.csv.</b></p>

| Column |Description | 
| :---- |:----- |
|`user_id`| the unique identifier of each user                                                                               |
|`attr_[1/2/3]`| general user attributes. Attr_1 and attr_2 are boolean, attrib_3 is categorical (can be integer [0,1,2,3,4])|
|`age`| The user's reported age.                                                                                             |
|`domain`| The user's top-level email domain. Less common domains are bundled together under the label 'other'.              |

### Distribution of data

First, let us see if our target variable is balanced meaning there are almost equal count of users who opened their emails and not.


```python
display(HTML('''<p style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;"><b>
Figure 1. Class distribution on train data</b></p>'''))

display(HTML(f'''<h3>
                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
                &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
                Most users <b style="color:#FF6600">
                do not</b> open their emails
                </h3>'''))


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 5))
bar_data = df_train['open_flag'].value_counts()
bar_data.index = ['Did not open', 'Opened']
ax = sns.barplot(x=bar_data.index, y=bar_data.values, color='lightslategrey', 
                 ax=ax, alpha=0.8)

# remove the frame of the chart
for spine in plt.gca().spines.values():
    spine.set_visible(False)

ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='both', length=0)
ax.axes.yaxis.set_ticks([]);
for bar in ax.containers[0]:
    plt.gca().text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, bar.get_height() - 5000, 
                   str(int(bar.get_height())), 
                 ha='center', color='w', fontsize=11)

ax.containers[0][0].set_color('#FF6600')
```

Let us now check the distribution of our features from train and test data using histograms.


```python
display(HTML('''<center style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;"><b>
Figure 2. Distribution of features on train and test data</b></center>'''))

i, j = 0, 0
fig, axes = plt.subplots(5, 2, figsize = (15, 20))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = .45)

for col in df_train.columns[1:]:
    if col in ['user_id', 'grass_date', 'row_id', 'open_flag', 
              'last_login_day', 'last_checkout_day', 'last_open_day']:
        continue
    else:
        sns.histplot(df_test[col], ax=axes[i,j], 
                     label='test', color='blue', alpha=0.7,
                     kde=True, stat="density", linewidth=0)
        sns.histplot(df_train[col], ax=axes[i,j], 
                     label='train', color='orange', alpha=0.7, 
                     kde=True, stat="density", linewidth=0)
        
        axes[i,j].legend()
    axes[i, j].set_title(col)
    axes[i, j].spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    axes[i, j].spines['right'].set_visible(False)
    
    j += 1 
    if j == 2:
        i += 1
        j = 0
```


<center style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;"><b>
Figure 2. Distribution of features on train and test data</b></center>



![png](output_26_1.png)


<b>Insights:</b>
- Most of the features are right skewed
- Train and test data came from the same distribution

Let's also see on how our users.csv distributed.


```python
display(HTML('''<center style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;"><b>
Figure 3. Distribution on train and test data</b></center>'''))


i, j = 0, 0
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize = (15, 20))
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = .45)

for col in df_users.columns[1:]:
    if col in ['user_id']:
        continue
    elif col == 'age':
        sns.histplot(df_users[col], ax=axes[i,j], color='#FF6600', 
                     kde=True, stat="density", linewidth=0)
    else:
        bar_data = df_users[col].value_counts()
        bars = axes[i,j].bar(bar_data.index, bar_data.values, color='#FF6600')
        
        for bar in bars:
            axes[i,j].text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, bar.get_height() 
                           + 1000, str(int(bar.get_height())), 
                 ha='center', color='gray', fontsize=11)
        if i == 2 and j == 0:
            for item in axes[i,j].xaxis.get_ticklabels():
                item.set_rotation(90)
        
    axes[i, j].set_title(col)
    axes[i, j].spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    axes[i, j].spines['right'].set_visible(False)
    
    j += 1 
    if j == 2:
        i += 1
        j = 0

fig.delaxes(axes[2,1])
```

### Correctness of Data

We now check if the open/login/checkout days are consistent to each other.


```python
print('Train:')
for activity in ['open', 'login', 'checkout']:
    for initdays, findays in zip([10, 30], [30, 60]):
        initcol =  '{}_count_last_{}_days'.format(activity, initdays)
        fincol = '{}_count_last_{}_days'.format(activity, findays)
        count = len(df_train[(df_train[initcol] > df_train[fincol])])
        print(f'Count of {initcol} > {fincol}: {count}')
```

    Train:
    Count of open_count_last_10_days > open_count_last_30_days: 0
    Count of open_count_last_30_days > open_count_last_60_days: 0
    Count of login_count_last_10_days > login_count_last_30_days: 0
    Count of login_count_last_30_days > login_count_last_60_days: 0
    Count of checkout_count_last_10_days > checkout_count_last_30_days: 0
    Count of checkout_count_last_30_days > checkout_count_last_60_days: 0
    



### Step 4. Handle Categorical Data

Create a function that would convert the categorical variables to one hot encode when the model is not catboost


```python
def category_transform(df):
    """
    One hot encode categorical variables if model != catboost
    """
    # Get one hot encoding of categorical columns
    for cat in ['country_code', 'weekday', 'domain']:
        one_hot_encode = pd.get_dummies(df[cat], prefix=cat)
        # Drop column as it is now encoded
        df = df.copy()
        df.drop(cat, axis=1, inplace=True)
        # Join the encoded df
        df = df.join(one_hot_encode)
        
    return df
```

### Step 5: Feature Transformation

Convert never open/login/checkout to the max value of the feature. Setting it to max value would make it appear to be "never".


```python
for i in ['checkout', 'login', 'open']:
    i = f'last_{i}_day'
    max_count = (df_train_merge[df_train_merge[i].str.isdecimal()]
                    [i].astype('int32').max())
    df_train_merge.loc[~df_train_merge[i].str.isdecimal(), 
                       i] = str(max_count)
    df_test_merge.loc[~df_test_merge[i].str
                      .isdecimal(), i] = str(max_count)
    df_train_merge[i] = df_train_merge[i].astype('int32')
    df_test_merge[i] = df_test_merge[i].astype('int32')
```

Convert the grass date to days of week. 


```python
def get_date_features(df):
    # Convert date to weekday
    df['grass_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['grass_date'])
    df['weekday'] = df['grass_date'].apply(lambda x: 
                                           x.weekday())
    df = df.drop('grass_date', axis=1)
    return df
```


```python
df_train_merge = get_date_features(df_train_merge)
df_test_merge = get_date_features(df_test_merge)
```

To reduce the correlation between <code>open_count_last_10_days</code> and <code>open_count_last_30_days</code>, etc. We can convert it to <code>open_count_10_to_30_days</code> since <code>open_count_last_10_days</code> already represents users on that duration.


```python
def transform_range(df):
    """
    Convert from last 30/60 days to 10/30 to 30/60
    """
    for activity in ['open', 'login', 'checkout']:
        for initdays, findays in zip([10, 30], [30, 60]):
            initcol =  '{}_count_last_{}_days'.format(activity, initdays)
            fincol = '{}_count_last_{}_days'.format(activity, findays)
            newcol = '{}_count_{}_to_{}_days'.format(activity, 
                                                     initdays, findays)
            df[newcol] = df[fincol] - df[initcol]
            if initdays == 30:
                df.drop(initcol, axis=1, inplace=True)
                df.drop(fincol, axis=1, inplace=True)
    return df 
```


```python
df_train_merge = transform_range(df_train_merge)
df_test_merge = transform_range(df_test_merge)
```

### Step 6: Now let's run an automated Machine Learning to the above processed data


```python
class AutoML(object):
    def __init__(self, model_code):
        self.splits = []
        models = {
            # regressor
            # error based
            'lir': [LinearRegression, 'Linear Regression'],
            'rdg': [Ridge, 'Ridge Regression'],
            'lso': [Lasso, 'Lasso Regression'],
            # information based
            'dtr': [DecisionTreeRegressor, 'Decision Tree'],
            'rfr': [RandomForestRegressor, 'Random Forest'],
            'gbr': [GradientBoostingRegressor, 'GradientBoost'],

            'knr': [KNeighborsRegressor, 'knn Regression'],

            # classifier
            # error based
            'log': [LogisticRegression, 'Logistic Regression'],
            'svl': [LinearSVC, 'Linear SVM'],
            'svm': [SVC, 'SVM'],
            'cbc': [CatBoostClassifier, 'Catboost'],

            # information based
            'dtc': [DecisionTreeClassifier, 'Decision Tree'],
            'rfc': [RandomForestClassifier, 'Random Forest'],
            'gbc': [GradientBoostingClassifier, 'Gradient Boost'],
            # similarity based
            'knc': [KNeighborsClassifier, 'knn Classification'],
        }
        # multiple train
        self.summs = None
        self.test_model = None
        if isinstance(model_code, list):
            if all(map(lambda x: x in models, model_code)):
                self.model_code = model_code
                self.model = [models[i][0] for i in model_code]
                self.model_name = [models[i][1] for i in model_code]
            else:
                raise ValueError('invalid model_code!')
        else:
            if model_code not in models.keys():
                raise ValueError('invalid model_code!')
            self.model_code = model_code
            self.model = models[model_code][0]
            self.model_name = models[model_code][1]
        # used only for appending for model_name
        self.append = True

    def split_data(self, X, y, random_state=1337, shuffle=True,
                   method='train_test', num_trials=1, stratify=False, **kwargs):
        stratify_dict = {}
        if self.splits:
            return self.splits

        if method == 'train_test':
            if stratify:
                stratify_dict['stratify'] = y

            for i in range(num_trials):
                test_size = 0.2 if 'test_size' not in kwargs.keys(
                ) else kwargs['test_size']

                (X_train, X_test, 
                 y_train, y_test) = train_test_split(X, y,
                                                     test_size=test_size,
                                                     random_state=i,
                                                     shuffle=shuffle,
                                                     **stratify_dict)

                self.splits.append((X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test))
        elif method == 'kfold':
            n_splits = 8 if 'n_splits' not in kwargs.keys(
            ) else kwargs['n_splits']
            if stratify:
                kf = StratifiedKFold(
                    n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=shuffle, 
                    random_state=random_state)
                self.splits = [(X.iloc[i], X.iloc[j], y.iloc[i], y.iloc[j])
                               for (i, j) in kf.split(X, y)]
            else:
                kf = KFold(n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=shuffle,
                           random_state=random_state)
                self.splits = [(X.iloc[i], X.iloc[j], y.iloc[i], y.iloc[j])
                               for (i, j) in kf.split(X)]

        return self.splits

    def generate_summary(self,):
        if self.summs is not None:
            return self.summs
        return [self.model_name, self.test_score, self.matt_score,
                self.best_param,
                self.top_predictor, self.run_time]

    def plot_feature_importance(self, absol=True, sort=True):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 8))
        mean_coefs = self.mean_coefs.copy()
        feature_names = self.feature_names.copy()

        if absol:
            mean_coefs = np.abs(mean_coefs)

        if sort:
            feature_names = feature_names[np.argsort(np.abs(mean_coefs))]
            mean_coefs = sorted(np.abs(mean_coefs))
        ax.set_title(self.model_name)
        ax.barh(np.arange(self.coefs_count), mean_coefs, color='#FF6600')
        ax.set_yticks(np.arange(self.coefs_count))
        ax.set_yticklabels(feature_names)

    def plot_train_val(self, log_scale=False):
        # Initialize figure
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 6))
        plt.title(self.model_name, fontsize=16)
        values = [list(param.values())[0] for param in self.param_grid]

        if log_scale:
            plt.xscale('log')

        # Plot the spread of predictions
        ax.fill_between(
            values,
            np.mean(self.score_train, axis=0) +
            np.std(self.score_train, axis=0),
            np.mean(self.score_train, axis=0) -
            np.std(self.score_train, axis=0),
            color='tab:blue', alpha=0.10
        )
        ax.fill_between(
            values,
            np.mean(self.score_test, axis=0) + np.std(self.score_test, axis=0),
            np.mean(self.score_test, axis=0) - np.std(self.score_test, axis=0),
            color='tab:orange', alpha=0.10
        )
        # Plot mean of the predictions
        ax.plot(values, np.mean(self.score_train, axis=0), lw=3,
                label="training accuracy")
        ax.plot(values, np.mean(self.score_test, axis=0), lw=3,
                label="validation accuracy")

        plt.xlabel(list(self.param_grid[0].keys())[0])
        plt.legend()
        plt.ylabel('accuracy')

    def set_model_default_params(self, model):
        default_params = {
            'rfr': {'n_jobs': -1, 'n_estimators': 50},
            'rfc': {'n_jobs': -1, 'n_estimators': 50},
            'gbr': {'n_estimators': 50},
            'gbc': {'n_estimators': 50},
            'cbc': {'loss_function': 'Logloss', 'class_weights': {0: 1, 1: 2},
                    'learning_rate': 0.1, 'logging_level': 'Silent',
                    'task_type': 'CPU'}
        }

        if self.model_code in default_params.keys():
            model.set_params(**default_params[self.model_code])

        elif self.model_code == 'log':
            if ('penalty' in self.fixed_params.keys() 
                and self.fixed_params['penalty'] == 'l1'):
                default_params = {'solver': 'liblinear'}
            else:
                default_params = {'dual': False}

            model.set_params(**default_params)
            if self.append:
                self.model_name = f'''{self.model_name} 
                ({self.fixed_params["penalty"]})'''
                self.append = False

        elif self.model_code == 'svl':
            if ('penalty' in self.fixed_params.keys() 
                and self.fixed_params['penalty'] == 'l1'):
                default_params = {'loss': 'squared_hinge', 'dual': False}
                model.set_params(**default_params)
            if self.append:
                self.model_name = f'''{self.model_name} 
                ({self.fixed_params["penalty"]})'''
                self.append = False

        return model

    def get_coefs(self, reg):
        if self.model_code in ['dtr', 'dtc',
                               'rfr', 'rfc',
                               'gbr', 'gbc',
                               'cbc']:
            coefs = reg.feature_importances_
        elif self.model_code in ['lir', 'rdg', 'lso', 'log', 'svl']:
            coefs = reg.coef_
        elif self.model_code in ['knr', 'knc']:
            coefs = None

        return coefs

    def train_model(self, X, y,
                    random_state=0, fixed_params={},
                    param_grid={'max_depth': range(2, 11)},
                    normalize=False, plot_train_val=True,
                    plot_feat_imp=True, resample=None):
        if isinstance(self.model_code, list):
            self.train_models_multiple(X, y,
                                       random_state, fixed_params,
                                       param_grid,
                                       normalize, plot_train_val,
                                       plot_feat_imp)
            return

        start_time = time.time()
        score_train = []
        score_test = []
        test_score = []
        training_score = []
        weighted_coefs = []
        param_grid = list(ParameterGrid(param_grid))
        model = self.model
        self.fixed_params = fixed_params
        self.normalize = normalize

        with tqdm(total=len(self.splits), file=sys.stdout,
                  position=0, leave=True) as pbar:
            for split in self.splits:
                pbar.set_description(self.model_name)

                training_accuracy = []
                training_scores = []
                test_accuracy = []
                test_scores = []
                X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = split

                if normalize:
                    # normalize the features
                    Scaler = normalize().fit(X_train)
                    X_train = Scaler.transform(X_train)
                    X_test = Scaler.transform(X_test)

                if resample:
                    X_train, y_train = resample.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

                if self.model_code in ['lir']:
                    mdl = model()
                    mdl.fit(X_train, y_train)
                    training_accuracy.append(mdl.score(X_train, y_train))
                    test_accuracy.append(mdl.score(X_test, y_test))
                    coefs = self.get_coefs(mdl)
                    weighted_coefs.append(coefs)
                else:
                    for param in param_grid:
                        try:
                            mdl = model(random_state=random_state,
                                        **param)
                        except TypeError:
                            mdl = model(**param)

                        mdl = self.set_model_default_params(mdl)
                        try:
                            mdl.set_params(**fixed_params)
                        except KeyError:
                            pass

                        mdl.fit(X_train, y_train)

                        training_accuracy.append(mdl.score(X_train, y_train))
                        y_hat = mdl.predict(X_train)
                        training_scores.append(
                            matthews_corrcoef(y_train, y_hat))
                        test_accuracy.append(mdl.score(X_test, y_test))
                        y_hat = mdl.predict(X_test)
                        test_scores.append(matthews_corrcoef(y_test, y_hat))

                        coefs = self.get_coefs(mdl)
                        weighted_coefs.append(coefs)
                pbar.update(1)

                score_train.append(training_accuracy)
                training_score.append(training_scores)
                score_test.append(test_accuracy)
                test_score.append(test_scores)

        # get the mean of the weighted coefficients over all the trials
        mean_coefs = None if self.model_code in [
            'knr', 'knc'] else np.mean(weighted_coefs, axis=0)
        mean_coefs = (None if self.model_code in ['knr', 'knc']
                      else (mean_coefs if mean_coefs.ndim == 1 
                            else mean_coefs.mean(axis=0)))
        score = np.mean(test_score, axis=0)
        top_predictor = 'NA' if self.model_code in [
            'knr', 'knc'] else X.columns[np.argmax(np.abs(mean_coefs))]

        # for plotting train and test accuracy
        self.score_train = score_train
        self.score_test = score_test
        self.param_grid = param_grid

        # for plotting feature importance
        self.mean_coefs = None if self.model_code in [
            'knr', 'knc'] else mean_coefs
        self.coefs_count = None if self.model_code in [
            'knr', 'knc'] else len(self.mean_coefs)
        self.feature_names = X.columns

        # for summary
        self.matt_score = np.amax(score)
        self.test_score = np.mean(score_test, axis=0)[np.argmax(score)]
        best_param = [f'{key} =  {value}'
                      for key, value in param_grid[np.argmax(score)].items()]
        self.best_param = ';'.join(
            best_param) if self.model_code != 'lir' else 'NA'
        self.top_predictor = top_predictor
        self.run_time = (time.time() - start_time)

        # for score
        self.test_param = param_grid[np.argmax(score)]

        if plot_train_val:
            if self.model_code == 'lir':
                pass
            elif self.model_code not in ['log', 'svl']:
                self.plot_train_val()
            else:
                self.plot_train_val(log_scale=True)

        if plot_feat_imp:
            if self.model_code not in ['knr', 'knc']:
                self.plot_feature_importance()

    def train_models_multiple(self, X, y,
                              random_state=0, fixed_params={},
                              param_grid={'max_depth': range(2, 11)},
                              normalize=False, plot_train_val=True,
                              plot_feat_imp=True):
        """should have the same params"""
        model_codes = self.model_code
        models = self.model
        model_names = self.model_name
        summs = []
        for model_code, model, model_name in zip(model_codes, models, model_names):
            self.append = True
            self.model_code = model_code
            self.model = model
            self.model_name = model_name
            self.train_model(X, y, random_state, fixed_params,
                             param_grid,
                             normalize, plot_train_val,
                             plot_feat_imp)
            summs.append(self.generate_summary())

        summs = pd.DataFrame(summs)
        summs.columns = ['Machine Learning Method', 'Test Accuracy', 'MCC',
                         'Best Parameter', 'Top Predictor Variable', 'Run Time']

        self.summs = summs

    def score(self, X, y):
        """ Works for single model only"""
        if self.test_model is None:
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = self.splits[0]

            if self.normalize:
                # normalize the features
                Scaler = self.normalize().fit(X_train)
                X_train = Scaler.transform(X_train)
                X_test = Scaler.transform(X_test)
                self.test_scaler = Scaler

            test_model = self.model()
            test_model = self.set_model_default_params(test_model)
            try:
                test_model.set_params(**self.fixed_params)
            except KeyError:
                pass

            test_model.set_params(**self.test_param)
            test_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
            self.test_model = test_model

        if self.normalize:
            X = self.test_scaler.transform(X)

        return self.test_model.score(X, y)
```

### i. Matthews Correlation Coefficient 

<p style="text-align:justify">Matthews Correlation Coefficient (MCC) is used when it is important to have a good accuracy at the four quadrants of the confusion matrix. As we can see in the formula:</p>

<p style="font-size:12px;font-style:default;"><b>
Figure 12. MCC formula</b></p>

<img src="data:image/png;base64,">

Matthews Correlation Coefficient solves the problem of being asymmetric of f1 score and the problem of being sensitive to class imbalance for accuracy$^3$. It ranges from -1 to 1 with 1 being perfectly prediction.

### iii. Resampling Method

- SMOTE
- ADASYN
- SMOTE-NC

<p style="text-align:justify">SMOTE-NC (or Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique-Nominal Continuous) is a variation of SMOTE that handles both numerical and categorical features. Compared to SMOTE, the difference of categorical features is now considered when computing for the median and k-nearest neighbors. The values for said features are then determined based on the values appearing for most of the k-nearest neighbors. To determine the categorical features, the implementation of this resampling technique in ‘imblearn’ requires a list of indices that represent these features.</p>



## F. Model Interpretability

### i. SHAP

<p style="text-align:justify">The first thing that we want to see is the feature importance and how it affects the model. We can see that by using Shapley values and more specifically Summary plot. The summary plot combines feature importance with feature effects. Each point on the summary plot is a Shapley value for a feature and an instance. It is arrange from top to bottom on how important the feature is.</p>


```python
# get x and y 
X = category_transform(df_train_merge).drop('open_flag', axis=1)
y = category_transform(df_train_merge)['open_flag']
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y,
                                                    test_size=0.25,
                                                    random_state=143, 
                                                    shuffle=True,
                                                    stratify=y)
# resample using SMOTE
resample = SMOTE(sampling_strategy=0.6, 
                 n_jobs=-1, 
                 random_state=143, 
                 k_neighbors=3)
X_train, y_train = resample.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# train model
params = {'loss_function' : 'Logloss', 'class_weights': {0:1, 1:2},
          'learning_rate' : 0.1,'logging_level':'Silent', 
          'max_depth' :4 }
model = CatBoostClassifier(**params)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Compute for shap values and plot
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(model, X_test)

shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_test)

shap.summary_plot(shap_values=shap_values[:, :16], 
                  features=X_test.iloc[:, :16], 
                  feature_names=X_test.columns[:16])
```

    100%|===================| 18367/18385 [05:55<00:00]       


![png](output_120_1.png)


<p style="text-align:justify">The results of summary plot shows that the history of the open count of a user highly determines its tendency to open an email again. Interstingly we can also see that the subject line length shows that the shorter the subject is then it is more likely to be opened by the user. In addition, age seems to correlate with the tendency of a user to open. We can see that the older the user is then it has more tendency to open an email again. </p>

### ii. Accumulated Local Effects (ALE) Plot

Using ALE Plot which is similar to PDP but uses a small window of feature instead of all data instances. With this, it solve the problem of PDP plots that it treats all of the features independent to each other and hence create instances that are impossible to happen in real life scenario.


```python
# ale plot of open count last 10 days
cm.rc("figure", figsize=(9, 6))
ale_plot(
    model,
    X_test,
    'open_count_last_10_days',
    bins=20,
)
```


![png](output_124_0.png)





    <matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f0afe150410>



We can see for the open count last 10 days that there is a rapid increase on the first four counts then slowly grow as the count increases


```python
# ale plot of subject line length
cm.rc("figure", figsize=(9, 6))
ale_plot(
    model,
    X_test,
    'subject_line_length',
    bins=20,
)
```


![png](output_126_0.png)





    <matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f0afe18a5d0>



For the subject line length, there is a sweet spot in 40 to 50 characters.


```python
# plot second order ALE plot
cm.rc("figure", figsize=(9, 6))
ale_plot(
    model,
    X_test,
```

### iii. RuleFit

The RuleFit algorithm learns sparse linear models that include automatically detected interaction effects in the form of decision rules. It uses a tree based model then evaluate it on lasso regression to reduce the number of rules. It has 5 major components: Rule, Type, Coef, Support, Feature Importance.


```python
# Create and Train RuleFit Model
rulefit = RuleFit(tree_generator=RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators = 100))
rulefit.fit(X.values, y, feature_names=X.columns)

# calculate rmse
rulefit_preds = rulefit.predict(X.values)
rulefit_rmse = np.sqrt(((rulefit_preds - y) ** 2).mean())
print(rulefit_rmse)
# get rules
rules = rulefit.get_rules()
rules = rules.sort_values('support', ascending=False)
rules
```

```python
# Get the rules
rules = rulefit.get_rules() 
# Eliminate the existing explanatory variables
rules = rules[rules['type']!='linear'] 
# eliminate the insignificant rules
rules = rules[rules['coef'] != 0] 
# Sort the rules based on "support" value
rules = rules.sort_values('support', ascending=False) 

# get rules without duplicate features
rule_split = rules.rule.str.split(' <= | >= | > | < | & ')
rules[rule_split.apply(lambda x:[i for i in x if len(i) > 3])
      .apply(lambda x : len(set(x)) == len(x))]
```

## G. Conclusion

<p style="text-align:justify">Shopee is the leading e-commerce in southeast Asia and continuously growing amidst the pandemic$^1$. They started their operation in Singapore in 2015. They could expand to 10 more countries in just six years, namely the Philippines, Malaysia, Thailand, Taiwan, Indonesia, Vietnam, Brazil, Mexico, Chile, and Colombia. One of the secrets to its success is its sophisticated business model that uses Artificial Intelligence to gather insights from the users.$^2$.</p>

<p style="text-align:justify">In this study, I explored one of the applications of AI in marketing: Predicting when a user would open an email sent by Shopee. I started by performing exploratory data analysis on the distribution, correlation, and correction of our data and finding useful patterns that can be used for our analysis. I saw that most of the users do not open/login/checkout within two months, but those who open an email recently are most likely to open it again. I then see that age slightly plays a factor in the opening of emails by Shopee. As it turns out, older people tend to read an email compared to the younger generation. On a side note, by performing exploratory data analysis, I also saw that our dataset is not that clean where I got an age that is negative and too high of a number that is older than that of the oldest person in the world. It seems that at the time they created the dataset, there was a problem in the app of Shoppee, where a user can enter any birthdate.
</p>

<p style="text-align:justify">I proceeded by performing data processing to prepare our data for our machine learning model. I used some techniques for imputing null values and feature engineering to help our model better understand the data. I then trained eight different models using a stratified train test split on ten trials with a 25% test size and found that the best-performing model in terms of prediction is Catboost. To improve the accuracy, I then performed resampling methods such as SMOTE, ADASYN, and SMOTENC, which further boosted the accuracy by 1%</p>
    
<p style="text-align:justify">I then used model interpretability and saw how the features affect the target variable in the summary plot. I noticed that a high open count of users tends to open an email again. I also noticed that subject line length and age play an important role in the model's decision. I then inspected features using the Accumulated Local Effects (ALE) Plot that I think are relevant to the study and further verified the results. I then used the RuleFit model to create rule-based decisions and saw that some countries do not prefer email as a platform.</p>

<p style="text-align:justify">Some of my recommendation to Shopee drawn from the models is that they can: Understand existing users who recently opened their email because they are likely to open it again, There is an optimal subject line length of 40 to 50 characters, and Consider targeting older people as they are more likely to read mails, and be aware on the country of the user because some countries may not prefer email as a medium at all.</p>
